value.value: Human AAMP wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 2q35 and is approximately 6 kb in length. This allele, which encodes angio-associated migratory cell protein, plays a role in cell adhesion and migration.
Angio-associated migratory cell protein (434 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human AAMP gene. This protein is involved in heparin binding, angiogenesis and smooth muscle cell migration.
This gene plays a role in RNA binding and mRNA decay.
This gene plays a role in transcriptional regulation and in vitamin D3 metabolism.

Human CSDE1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 1p13.2 and is approximately 42 kb in length. This allele, which encodes cold shock domain-containing protein E1, is involved in translationally-coupled mRNA turnover.
Cold shock domain-containing protein E1 (798 aa, ~89 kDa) is encoded by the human CSDE1 gene. This protein plays a role in mRNA decay.
This gene is involved in the synthesis of lacto- or neolacto-containing glycolipids.

Human B3GNT5 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 3q27.1 and is approximately 45 kb in length. This allele, which encodes lactosylceramide 1,3-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyltransferase protein, plays a role in the elongation of carbohydrate chains on glycolipids.

Lactosylceramide 1,3-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyltransferase (378 aa, ~44 kDa) is encoded by the human B3GNT5 gene. This protein is involved in the synthesis of lacto- or neolacto-series carbohydrate chains on glycolipids.
The presence of more than one plasmacytoma arising in the bone, concurrently or sequentially, in the absence of bone marrow involvement by plasma cell myeloma.
This gene plays a role in the structure of select endothelial and subendothelial extracellular matrixes and basement membranes.

label.value: Extramedullary Disease in Multiple Myeloma Involving the Central Nervous System

value.value: Multiple myeloma involving the central nervous system. It manifests with single or multiple intraparenchymal lesions and/or leptomeningeal involvement. Patients present with diffuse cerebral dysfunction and nerve paralysis. The prognosis is poor.

Human COL8A1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 3q12.1 and is approximately 161 kb in length. This allele, which encodes collagen alpha-1(VIII) chain protein, is involved in the organization of the basement membrane or extracellular matrix.

label.value: Extramedullary Disease in Multiple Myeloma Involving the Leptomeninges

value.value: A central nervous system multiple myeloma involving the leptomeninges.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and apoptosis. It also plays a role in the regulation of both steroid synthesis and T-cell response.
Collagen alpha-1(VIII) chain (744 aa, ~73 kDa) is encoded by the human COL8A1 gene. This protein plays a role in the structure of Descemet's membrane and blood vessel endothelium.
A plasmacytoma that arises in the spleen.
A plasmacytoma that arises in the liver.
A plasmacytoma that arises in the lung.
A plasmacytoma that arises in the skin.
This gene may be involved in the suppression of oncogene expression.
Human MIR766 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of Xq24 and is approximately 1 kb in length. This allele, which encodes MIR766 pre-miRNA, may play a role in tumor suppression.
MIR766 pre-miRNA (111 bases) is encoded by the human MIR766 gene. This oligoribonucleotide may be involved in transcriptional silencing and tumor suppression.
A 22 ribonucleotide sequence that is a final product of the processing of MIR766 pre-miRNA. This oligonucleotide may play a role in the negative regulation of expression for CBP, BRD4 and MYC.

A radioconjugate composed of an isatin sulfonamide analog labeled with the positron-emitting isotope fluorine F 18, with potential imaging activity for activated caspase-3, which is a marker for apoptosis, using positron emission tomography/computed tomography (PET/CT). Upon administration, fluorine F 18 WC-4-116 is preferentially taken up by and accumulates in cells with high caspase-3 activity. Upon PET/CT imaging, caspase-3 activation may be detected, and apoptotic activity, including chemotherapy-induced tumor apoptosis, may be assessed. Caspase-3, a cysteine protease, plays an important role in apoptosis.

Short Tandem Repeat Polymorphism consists of variation between individuals in the number of repeat units of Simple Tandem Repeats at a specific location in the genome. These are used extensively as markers in gene mapping and linkage analysis.

label.value: HPV Status Correlated to CDKN2A-p16 Expression Status

value.value: An indication of whether a neoplastic sample is positive or negative for expression of CDKN2A-p16. Positive expression of CDKN2A-p16 indicates that the tumor is related to a current or prior HPV infection, especially infections caused by high-risk HPV genotypes.
This gene is involved in the metabolism of gangliosides and glycoproteins.

Human ST8SIA6 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 10p12.33 and is approximately 141 kb in length. This allele, which encodes alpha-2,8-sialyltransferase 8F protein, plays a role in the synthesis gangliosides and the modification of glycoproteins.
Alpha-2,8-sialyltransferase 8F (398 aa, ~45 kDa) is encoded by the human ST8SIA6 gene. This protein is involved in the synthesis of sialylglycoconjugates on proteins and lipids.
This gene plays a role in regulation of synaptic vesicle exocytosis.

Human RIMS1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 6q13 and is approximately 517 kb in length. This allele, which encodes regulating synaptic membrane exocytosis protein 1, is involved in release of neurotransmitters and insulin. Mutation of the gene is associated with cone-rod dystrophy 7.
Regulating synaptic membrane exocytosis protein 1 (1692 aa, ~189 kDa) is encoded by the human RIMS1 gene. This protein plays a role in synaptic vesicle exocytosis.
This gene is involved in promoting the activation of JAK/STAT signaling pathways.
Human OCIAD2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 4p11 and is approximately 22 kb in length. This allele, which encodes OCIA domain-containing protein 2, plays a role in STAT3 activation.
OCIA domain-containing protein 2 (154 aa, ~17 kDa) is encoded by the human OCIAD2 gene. This protein is involved in the activation of JAK/STAT signaling pathways.

A family of cellular proteins encoded by the c-erbB genes, including epidermal growth factor receptor. They are normally expressed in a variety of tissues of epithelial, mesenchymal, and neuronal origin.  They are overexpressed in a significant portion of adenocarcinomas found at various sites, especially in the breast. Gene amplification appears to be the predominant method leading to overexpression.
This gene plays a role in transcriptional regulation, histone metabolism, cell differentiation, cell adhesion and cell migration.

Human PRDM5 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 4q27 and is approximately 238 kb in length. This allele, which encodes PR domain zinc finger protein 5, is involved in histone modification, transcriptional repression and hematopoiesis. Mutation of the gene is associated with brittle cornea syndrome 2.

PR domain zinc finger protein 5 (630 aa, ~73 kDa) is encoded by the human PRDM5 gene. This protein plays a role in transcriptional repression, cell differentiation, cell adhesion, cell migration and recruitment of histone methyltransferases and histone deacetylases.
This gene is involved in potassium channel regulation and calcium-dependent phospholipid scramblase activity.

Human ANO3 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11p14.2 and is approximately 479 kb in length. This allele, which encodes anoctamin-3 protein, plays a role in phospholipid metabolism and potassium channel activity regulation. Mutation of the gene is associated with dystonia 24.
Anoctamin-3 (981 aa, ~115 kDa) is encoded by the human ANO3 gene. This protein is involved in increasing potassium channel sodium sensitivity and phospholipid scramblase activity.
An adaptation of whole-brain radiation therapy that uses intensity-modulated radiation therapy to reduce the radiation dose to the hippocampus.
Fibrolamellar carcinoma that has spread extensively to other anatomic sites or is no longer responding to treatment.
Hilar cholangiocarcinoma that is not amenable to surgical resection.
Hilar cholangiocarcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.

Retrovirus-associated DNA sequences originally isolated from, or related to, the avian erythroblastosis virus (AEV). The c-erbA proto-oncogene encodes the thyroid hormone receptors, and the c-erbB family codes for the epidermal growth factor receptor (erbB-1, EGFR) and related receptors (erbB-2, erbB-3).
Hilar cholangiocarcinoma that has spread extensively to other anatomic sites or is no longer responding to treatment.
Extrahepatic bile duct carcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.
